VCompanies Continue The Rush to Combine Mergers and acquisitions seem to have become a constant in the business landscape, works-in-progress more unceasing than construction in Manhattan. Most major industries contributed to the record level of deals last year: In banking and financial services, First Union agreed to buy Corestates; Travelers Group, which already owns Smith Barney, added Salomon, and Dean Witter, Discover joined Morgan Stanley to form a Wall Street giant. The consolidation in aerospace and high technology continued with Lockheed Martin's acquisition of Northrop Grumman. Perhaps not surprisingly, one of the more engaging takeover battles -- the fight for ITT between Hilton and Starwood Lodging, the eventual winner -- involved companies in the gambling and hotel businesses. But the biggest deal of all was in telecommunications, where Worldcom trumped its rivals, GTE and British Telecommunications, in a grab for MCI Communications.
