VFor months, Wall Street has been begging the Westinghouse Electric Corporation to split itself up. Without its sluggish industrial side, the theory goes, Westinghouse, which bought CBS for $5.4 billion last summer and is now spending $4.9 billion for the huge Infinity Broadcasting radio operation, would be a pure media company that could command share prices more than double the $15 or so at which the stock has been mired for several years. Michael H. Jordan, the Westinghouse chief executive who pieced together the odd mix in the first place, now agrees with the Street, and the company is studying ways to engineer such a split. But there is one question Mr. Jordan seems not yet ready to answer: What will happen to the five businesses that make up Westinghouse's $5.5 billion industries and technology group, whose lackluster performance drove Westinghouse into the media camp in the first place?
