asS'199603'
p152
(lp153
VThe Northrop Grumman Corporation said yesterday that it would dismiss 2,100 people from its military aircraft division in Southern California by the end of the year. Northrop Grumman, the military contractor, employs about 12,500 people in the region. It said declining work on its two major aircraft programs, the B-2 Stealth bomber and the F/A-18 attack fighter, made the cuts necessary. The planned reductions also arise from cost cuts on the version of the F/A-18 that is now in production. Northrop Grumman, which is based in Los Angeles, said that most of the cuts would be made by July 1.
p154
aVThe United States economy gained strength last month even though a midwinter lull in aircraft purchases caused factory orders to fall by the largest percentage in 10 months, the Commerce Department reported today. While overall orders dropped 2.5 percent in February -- as demand for passenger jets weakened -- analysts pointed to a seven-tenths of 1 percent increase in orders excluding transportation equipment as a sign that a spring rebound for the economy was likely.
