VThe Northrop Grumman Corporation, the military contractor, detailed two proposals today that it plans to take to a shareholder meeting of TRW Inc. in April urging TRW's board to reconsider its $5.9 billion takeover offer. The proposals call for TRW to set up a committee of independent directors to consider Northrop's $47-a-share unsolicited bid and to give Northrop access to crucial financial information.
p318
aVTRW Inc. advised shareholders yesterday to reject two proposals made by the Northrop Grumman Corporation, which has made a $6 billion takeover bid for TRW. The proposals, disclosed in a Securities and Exchange Commission filing last week, call on TRW's board to provide Northrop with nonpublic financial information and to establish a committee of independent directors to review Northrop's $47-a-share takeover bid. The bid is more than $4 a share below TRW's current market value. TRW formally rejected Northrop's offer earlier this month, calling it inadequate, and proposed instead to spin off its auto parts unit and sell the TRW Aeronautical Systems Group. TRW is based in Cleveland, and Northrop is based in Los Angeles.
p319
aVLAST fall, when Boeing's bid to build the F-35 Joint Strike Fighter flamed out and the $200 billion winner-take-all contract to supply up to 3,000 planes went to its rival, Lockheed Martin, a good part of Boeing's plans went up in smoke. Designed for the Air Force, the Navy and the Marines, the F-35 will be the last new manned American fighter for decades to come. But, as things turned out, Boeing's warplane operations were set back only momentarily. The company is moving on to the next generation of combat planes: robotic, pilotless aircraft.
