VThe Northrop Grumman Corporation, in the midst of an attempt to buy a rival military contractor, the TRW Corporation, for $6.7 billion, said yesterday that it refused to sign a confidentiality agreement that would have opened TRW's financial records for inspection. Northrop Grumman said the agreement contained restrictions, like a a standstill clause, that it regarded as onerous. Northrop Grumman also encouraged TRW's shareholders to urge the company's directors to consider the bid, which amounts to $53 a share, when TRW holds its annual meeting tomorrow. TRW, which is based in Cleveland, has rejected Northrop Grumman's bid, saying it is too low. Northrop Grumman, which is based in Los Angeles, raised its bid from $5.9 billion a week ago.
p333
aVTRW said yesterday that it had signed a confidentiality agreement with ''several interested parties,'' two days after its shareholders asked management to share confidential financial information with the Northrop Grumman Corporation, which has made a $6.7 billion bid for the firm. TRW said that Northrop Grumman was invited to participate but it did not identify the parties that had signed the confidentiality agreement. Such an agreement gives potential bidders access to confidential financial information. TRW has said the offer from Northrop, based in Los Angeles, is too low. TRW, a military contractor, is based in Cleveland.
p334
aVTRW Inc., which received a higher takeover bid from the Northrop Grumman Corporation, advised its shareholders yesterday not to take any action while it reviewed the proposal. Northrop raised its bid to $6.7 billion from $5.9 billion on Sunday. TRW, a satellite and missile maker based in Cleveland, rejected the earlier bid as inadequate. The new offer is valued at $53 a share, compared with an original bid of $47 a share. Northrop Grumman, a military contractor based in Los Angeles, set a May 3 deadline for the offer to be accepted or rejected.
p335
aVThe Northrop Grumman Corporation said yesterday that it would not appeal a court ruling that allows TRW Inc. to delay a meeting on Northrop's $12.2 billion hostile bid for the company until May 3. The meeting, originally set for Monday, will let shareholders vote on a proposal made by Northrop that would allow it to begin buying TRW shares. Northrop also wants TRW to allow shareholders who are precluded from voting under Ohio law to be given a vote. TRW is scheduled to hold its annual meeting Wednesday in Cleveland, where it is based. Northrop, which is based in Los Angeles, is pursuing TRW to increase sales of military and aerospace electronics.
