VSeven of the nation's biggest military contractors are competing for a share of the largest aircraft project on the horizon: A new jet fighter for the Air Force at a cost of up to $50 billion. The seven companies filed ''technical proposals'' with the Government on Tuesday - each one a 3,000-page compendium explaining how it would design a replacement for the F-15, the Air Force's current medium-range fighter. The proposed plane is now called the Advanced Tactical Fighter, or A.T.F. Already each of the companies has spent millions of dollars of its own money in jockeying for a role in the project. 'Program for the 1990's ''It is a must-win program,'' said Herbert F. Rogers, a general manager of the General Dynamics Corporation, one of the competitors. The others are McDonnell Douglas, which makes the F-15, Boeing, Grumman, Lockheed, Northrop and Rockwell International.
