VAmerican companies, facing stiff competition from abroad and relaxed antitrust regulations at home, are banding together to cooperate in research and development at an unprecedented rate, according to corporate and Government officials. For the first time, the officials add, the cooperation has gone beyond dealing with such industrywide issues as controlling pollution to projects that could result in new products with broad commercial potential. The projects involve some of the country's biggest companies. Burroughs, I.B.M., Texas Instruments and other computer giants are members of the Semiconductor Research Corporation. Boeing, General Dynamics and Grumman are among 14 companies studying ways to develop computer software for military projects. And Hewlett-Packard and ITT are part of a fiber optics group.
