VTwo teams of aerospace industry giants are forming to seek an Air Force contract for the next generation of fighter aircraft, the companies said today. The Boeing Company, the General Dynamics Corporation and the Lockheed Corporation announced today that they would cooperate in an effort to obtain the project known as the Advanced Tactical Fighter. The Northrop Corporation and the McDonnell Douglas Corporation are in ''serious discussions'' to form a competing team, officials of the companies said.
p372
aVMilitary contractors around the country, after five years of the biggest peacetime arms buildup in American history, now are girding for austerity, bitter competition and more onerous demands from the Pentagon and Capitol Hill. It is not just that the military budget is level or even shrinking after soaring earlier in the decade. The broad efforts to narrow the Government's budget deficit, combined with growing doubts about the efficiency and conduct of contractors, are also resulting in major changes in the military procurement system. The stress now is on competition. Scrutiny of company practices has increased. And contractors are finding they must absorb more of the cost of developing new technologies. 'A Sustained Freeze' ''This is a watershed, largely to do with the total amount of spending,'' said Joshua M. Epstein, an analyst at the Brookings Institution in Washington. ''I don't think you'll see much growth in defense spending over the next four years; basically it'll be a sustained freeze.''
p373
aVISRAEL and the United States are locked in what could be the biggest air battle ever in the Middle East. Armed with calculators and cost estimates, the Pentagon is quietly trying to shoot down the 300 Lavi advanced fighter jets that Israel is proposing to build. Using some $1 billion in American aid money, Israel is rushing the Lavi off the drawing board, onto the production lines and into the air in hopes that once it is a reality not even the ablest Pentagon cost-cutters will be able to quash Israel's multi-role, state-of-the art fighter-bomber for the 1990's. Israel has taken the lead in this bizarre arms race by virtue of the fact that tomorrow the first two Lavi prototypes will have their official ''rollout'' for public viewing. Test flights should follow by October.
