VHanding the McDonnell-Douglas Corporation a major victory, the Defense Department said yesterday that it had decided to order 80 more of the company's C-17 military jet transport planes, in a contract it said was worth about $18 billion. McDonnell triumphed over an alternative proposal to buy a mix of 32 C-17's and 30 C-33's, the military freight version of the Boeing Company's 747 jumbo jet. Although the Boeing jet would have cost far less, Pentagon officials were said to favor a plane designed from the ground up for military use, with the ability to land on dirt runways and to unload cargo without additional equipment.
