VWINGATE INNS INTERNATIONAL wanted to hold its first chain-wide conference in a resort big enough to accommodate 305 people for four days, yet small enough to convey a sense of intimacy during meals and receptions. Because the working sessions would deal with financing, risk management and similarly unexciting topics, Wingate also wanted a range of recreational options where guests could unwind. And so it was that the owners and general managers of the 65 Wingate properties -- mid-priced hotels aimed at business travelers -- spent four days last month at the Chateau Elan Winery and Resort in Braselton, Ga., 30 minutes from Atlanta. In addition to the skull sessions, there were tournaments on both of the resort's golf courses, plus opportunities to play tennis, jog, indulge at the spa or hike the trails through the resort's 3,100 acres.
