VThe Northrop Grumman Corporation reported yesterday that earnings fell 85 percent in the fourth quarter because of declining military aircraft production and fewer orders for commercial jet fuselages. Northrop Grumman earned $17 million, or 24 cents a diluted share, on sales of $2.5 billion, down from $117 million, or $1.71 a share, on sales of $2.5 billion in the final quarter of 1997. The results were affected by the Boeing Company's decision to reduce production of its 747 passenger jet. Northrop, which builds 747 fuselages, has said it will cut 1,100 jobs in four states to deal with the Boeing cutback. Earnings were also hurt by a slowdown in B-2 bomber production, the company said.
