p514
aVIn what is expected to be the final chapter in the dizzyingly rapid consolidation of big American military contractors, the Lockheed Martin Corporation announced yesterday that it was buying the Northrop Grumman Corporation for $8.3 billion. The deal would reinforce Lockheed Martin's position as the largest weapons supplier to the Pentagon, creating a company with annual revenue of about $35 billion and more than 230,000 employees. It has emerged at the top of the industry, trailed by Boeing and Raytheon, after a swift stream of mergers propelled by the end of the cold war and sharp cuts in the military budget. While this process has been encouraged by the Clinton Administration, others have questioned whether too much of the market will be concentrated in a lineup of behemoths providing a broad array of products. $(Page D2.$)
