(lp542
VFORMER ENRON CHIEF DIES -- Kenneth L. Lay, who as founder of the Enron Corporation rose to peaks of influence in business and politics, only to fall into disgrace amid scandal, died in Aspen, Colo., while awaiting a judge's sentencing this fall that could have sent him to prison for decades. He was 64. [Pages A1 and C7.] LEGAL IMPACT -- Kenneth L. Lay's death effectively voids the guilty verdict against him, temporarily thwarting the federal government's efforts to seize his remaining real estate and financial assets, legal experts say. [C1.] OIL SURGES AFTER MISSILE TESTS -- Oil prices closed at a record high in New York as political tensions over the missile tests by North Korea shook equity and commodities markets around the world. In an already rattled oil market, North Korea's test of at least seven missiles, including one with long-range capability, gave traders another reason to push prices past $75 a barrel. [C1.] WHEN LARGE IS SMALL -- The Small Business Administration and other federal agencies are mandated by law to provide at least 23 percent of federal contracts to small businesses. But for years, government studies show, large corporations like GTSI, Boeing, General Dynamics and Northrop Grumman have been counted as small businesses. And despite some efforts by the federal government to correct the mistakes, problems persist. [C1.] NEW JERSEY SHUTDOWN -- As New Jersey's budget impasse deepened and the shutdown of state government services continued, Atlantic City's 12 casinos were forced to close for the first time in the 28 years that gambling has been legal there. [A1.] CONCERT PROMOTERS MAKE DEAL -- Live Nation Inc., the largest concert promoter in the United States, said that it had reached a deal to buy the No. 2 promoter, HOB Entertainment, the operator of the House of Blues clubs, for $350 million, in a further concentration of the live-music business. [C3.] GAS RIGHTS FOR GAZPROM -- Russia's Parliament passed a law that grants exclusive rights for exporting natural gas to Gazprom, the state-owned energy operator that is already the world's largest gas company. To take effect, the law must be signed by President Vladimir V. Putin, who has not commented on the legislation. [C4.] IMMIGRATION HEARINGS -- Lawmakers from the Senate and the House, at odds over immigration reform, held rival hearings on opposite coasts, competing for public support for their differing proposals and moving no closer to compromise. [A12.] WIRELESS INTERNET VENTURE -- Intel Capital and Motorola Ventures, the venture investment groups for the two chip makers, announced that together they would invest $900 million in Clearwire, a wireless Internet service provider, in hopes of speeding development of a global high-speed wireless network. [C7.] ATARI'S WAITING GAME -- When executives involved with Test Drive Unlimited, the ambitious online racing simulation due from Atari later this summer, start talking about the game, they trumpet its long, difficult and expensive production process, which began in 2003 and has cost of $15 million and $25 million. [E1.] FORCE BEHIND GATES FOUNDATION -- Melinda Gates, of the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, is far more than a name on the door. Although her husband, as the founder of Microsoft, is better known, she has played an instrumental role in the foundation's evolution from a modest-sized organization less than a decade ago into the world's largest foundation, with ambitious goals to reform education in America and eradicate the world's killer diseases. [A12.] END OF A COMPANY TOWN -- The Pacific Lumber Company has owned the entirety of Scotia, Calif., all 500 acres of it, for 140 years. But soon the company will sell almost all of its residential holdings to the employees who rent them, effectively putting an end to one of the last company towns in the United States. [A1.] CHAPPELLE'S LOST EPISODES -- Having been unable to persuade the comedian Dave Chappelle to return to his hit series, Comedy Central has pieced together sketches he did before his abrupt departure in May 2005 and named them ''Chappelle's Show: The Lost Episodes.'' [E1.] NEW FINANCIAL GUIDELINES -- A global group known as the Equator Principles Financial Institutions is expanding its guidelines for ensuring that the large projects they finance do not have a harmful impact on the environment or local population. [C11.] ONLINE ONLINE: DEALBOOK -- A report on mergers and acquisitions, up-to-the-minute news on Wall Street and a look at the behind-the-scenes maneuvering is at nytimes.com/dealbook. COMING TO GRIPS WITH CHANGE -- The story of Racine, Wis., like that of the nation as a whole, is the story of how a community comes to grips with the larger forces of globalization and technological change. A report is at nytimes.com/business. VICTIMS OF A COAL BOOM -- As coal powers China's sizzling economy, thousands of acres of land are literally sinking because of the ravages of underground coal mining. A report is at nytimes.com/business.
