VNews Analysis WASHINGTON, Feb. 3 - The Air Force's decision in the Great Engine War this evening was but one more turn, albeit a big one, in the long and convoluted struggle for this lucrative contract and, in fact, extended that competition well into the future. By splitting the production and holding the contract to one year, the Air Force will evidently try to exercise competitive pressures on both the General Electric Company and the Pratt & Whitney Aircraft Group, a unit of the United Technologies Corporation, to hold down costs, which has been among the main objectives of Secretary of Defense Caspar W. Weinberger. The Secretary of the Air Force, Verne Orr, who made the basic decision that was reviewed by Mr. Weinberger, appeared to have taken after his colleague, Secretary of the Navy John Lehman. Mr. Lehman has successfully played off the Grumman Corporation on one side and the McDonnell Douglas Corporation and the Northrop Corporation on the other to hold costs down on Navy planes. The decision, announced this evening, would have General Electric build 120 engines for the single-engine F-16 fighter, and Pratt & Whitney make 40 engines for the dual-engine F-15 fighter. The contract would be for a fixed price, which was not announced.
