(lp733
VThe push by American industry to produce better goods at lower cost appears to be working its way slowly onto the factory floors of many of the Pentagon's major contractors. Prodded by a new toughness in the Pentagon and Congress against cost overruns and poor quality of military hardware, the major arms contractors are installing new production systems and controls to keep costs down and quality up. In turn, the big primary contractors are putting pressure on their suppliers to shape up. ''These companies had a free license to spend and there was a lot of looseness,'' said Representative Joseph Patrick Addabbo, the Queens Democrat who is head of the House Subcommitee on Defense Procurement. ''Now, most contractors realize that the pressure is on to reduce costs. I think they are going to stay with it.''
