VFour military contractors have received federal contracts to study hypersonic weapons, including an unmanned bomber. The Northrop Grumman Corporation said yesterday that its six-month contract, from the Air Force and the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency, calls for it to develop concepts for a ''hypersonic cruise vehicle'' capable of flying at eight times the speed of sound and striking targets 9,000 miles away in less than two hours. A Northrop spokesman, Brooks McKinney, said the contract was valued at about $1.5 million. Similar initial-study contracts went to Northrop's primary competitors, the Lockheed Martin Corporation and the Boeing Company, and to the closely held Andrews Space in Seattle, a Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency spokeswoman, Jan Walker, said in an e-mail message.
