VMARKET STUMBLES -- Only a week ago, the Dow Jones industrial average seemed about to regain all that had been lost since the spectacular 1990's boom ended. But since then the stock market has ebbed, and yesterday the Dow tumbled yet again on a government report that showed consumer prices rising more than expected. The Dow fell 214.28 points closing at 11,205.61. [Page A1.] TAKING RISKS -- Four years into what has become the longest bull market in the brief, turbulent history of investing in emerging markets, investors from hedge funds to mutual funds to public and private pension funds have shown a willingness to take on increased levels of risk in such markets. [C1.] MEDICAL MYSTERY -- For Bausch & Lomb, a phone call from a New Jersey eye doctor in March was the first sign that a puzzling medical mystery that had surfaced in a few overseas markets might escalate into a safety problem involving a popular and lucrative product. [C1.] OFF THE BEATEN PATH -- The Iscar Metalworking Company, an Israeli maker of precision metal-cutting tools, has always operated outside the business mainstream. Now Warren E. Buffett has put up $4 billion to buy an 80 percent share. [C1.] SECURITY DATABASE -- Statements by company executives indicate that government efforts to obtain data from the largest phone companies for a national-security database appear to have focused on long-distance carriers, not local ones. [A23.] HONDA DROPS EARLY HYBRID -- American Honda said it was dropping the Insight, a quirky two-seater that was the first gasoline-electric hybrid vehicle sold in America. Honda is preparing to introduce a new hybrid vehicle in 2009. It also sells hybrid versions of its Civic and Accord. [C4.] 'VIRTUAL FENCE' -- Lockheed Martin, Raytheon and Northrop Grumman are among the companies that said they would submit bids for a federal contract to build a ''virtual fence'' along the nation's land borders. [A1.] BANK INQUIRY WIDENS -- A federal investigation of Deutsche Bank's role in questionable tax shelters has widened to include a broader array of shelters than previously known, people briefed on the inquiry said. [C4.] AUDIT RULES MODIFIED -- The Securities and Exchange Commission moved to make audit rules that have angered many companies easier and less expensive to apply. But despite political pressure, the S.E.C. said smaller companies would eventually have to comply. Market Place. [C1.] TIME NAMES TOP EDITOR -- Richard Stengel, 51, a longtime writer and editor at Time magazine and the former head of its Web site, was named its managing editor, the 16th person to hold the job in the magazine's 83-year history. Mr. Stengel, above, said that in some ways the Internet poses the same kind of challenge to newsweeklies that the plethora of competing newspapers posed to Time when it was founded in 1923. [C12.] SUPPORTING ROLES -- As the broadcast television networks present their prime-time schedules for the 2006-7 season, they are working almost as hard to promote the marketing opportunities inside their shows as those outside them during the commercial breaks. Advertising. [C10.] FOX SCHEDULE -- The Fox network has ordered four new dramas and three new comedies for next season. [B1.] HEART DEVICE RECALLS RISE -- As the use of life-saving emergency defibrillators has proliferated over the last decade, so has the number of devices recalled because of their potential to fail, according to data. [C4.] SECOND BID FOR MINING COMPANY -- The Canadian nickel miner Falconbridge became the target of a second takeover bid, a hostile all-cash offer from its largest shareholder, Xstrata of Switzerland. [C12.] MEXICAN GROWTH -- The Mexican government said the nation's economy expanded 5.5 percent in the first quarter. Economists pointed to the data as evidence that Mexican industry was recovering from the shock of Chinese competition. [C12.] ONLINE THE BUSINESS OF GREEN -- Businesses are going green for many reasons, not just to enhance their image. Some are seeking a competitive advantage. A special report is at nytimes.com/business. YOUR MONEY -- Look ahead at the news that will affect your finances with Your Money, a free weekly newsletter at nytimes.com/yourmoney. ONLINE: DEALBOOK -- As jurors deliberate the fate of Jeffrey K. Skilling and Kenneth L. Lay, DealBook looks at the odds making and futures trading that are taking place over a possible verdict, at nytimes.com/dealbook. Business Briefing Articles on these developments are at nytimes.com/business. THE ZALE CORPORATION, the nation's largest jewelry retailer, posted a better-than-expected quarterly profit. Profit was $16.8 million for the third quarter, up from $14.5 million a year earlier. (REUTERS) CIRCUIT CITY STORES said that sales in the quarter ''continued to be very strong,'' and it outlined a long-term profit-margin target that topped some expectations. (REUTERS) BURGER KING HOLDINGS priced an initial public offering worth $425 million. The offering of 25 million shares, 19 percent of the company, sold for $17 a share, at the high end of a forecast. (REUTERS) TALBOTS INC., the women's apparel retailer, said profit for the first quarter declined to $27.4 million, from $34.5 million. (REUTERS)
