aVCOMAPNIES For Northrop Grumman Workers, the Bad News Gets Very Specific It's no surprise, really. The country is laying down its weapons -- well, except in Haiti -- and that's putting a lot of people out of work. And when Northrop swallowed Grumman earlier this year, everyone knew that spelled more sizable job cuts. But still, when the big shoe dropped last week, the numbers were stark: Northrop Grumman, as it's now known, is reducing its work force by 8,650, or more than 18 percent, by the end of 1995. That's a "healthy response" to Pentagon cutbacks, said one consultant. But don't talk about health on, say, Long Island. In 1986, Grumman gave out 25,000 paychecks there, making it Long Island's largest private employer; those days are already history, of course, but the payroll will soon shrivel even more, to 3,800. The bulk of the latest layoffs, though, will come in California -- 4,150 of them. And that comes just after word that GM Hughes would lay off 4,400.
