aVTHE Grumman Corporation, the venerable Long Island military contractor whose future seemed dim, has suddenly emerged as a highly coveted jewel of the weapons industry. As Pentagon spending shrinks, the industry has consolidated, and there are few companies as big as Grumman left to buy -- or as willing to sell to survive. The Northrop Corporation, a competing weapons maker based in Los Angeles, ignited a bidding war for Grumman last week, making a $2.04 billion offer, or $60 a share, that topped a $1.9 billion bid, or $55 a share, made earlier in the week by the Martin Marietta Corporation.
