aVIn what appeared to set off a bidding war, the Northrop Corporation offered late yesterday to purchase the Grumman Corporation, the Long Island warplane manufacturer, for $60 a share, or $2.04 billion. The Northrop offer came three days after the Martin Marietta Corporation announced that it would purchase Grumman for $55 a share. The battle for Grumman underscores two aspects of weapons making in the post-cold war era. One is that Pentagon spending for weapons and research, projected at $88 billion this year, is still a very good business for the half-dozen or so manufacturers that survive as major military contractors. The other is that no matter which company -- Northrop or Martin Marietta -- wins Grumman, the new, merged concern will close plants and cut staff.
